  "prompt": "Why doesn't law focus on why you can fire someone from their job instead of why you can't?",
  "response": "Laws typically focus on protecting employees from unjust termination for several reasons:\n\n1. Historical context: Labor laws developed in response to past workplace abuses where workers had few rights and could be fired arbitrarily\n\n2. Power imbalance: Employers generally have more economic and legal power than individual employees\n\n3. Social protection: Preventing discrimination and ensuring fair treatment helps maintain economic stability and social justice\n\n4. Economic security: Protecting workers from arbitrary dismissal provides economic stability for individuals and families\n\n5. Preventing exploitation: Laws prevent employers from firing workers for discriminatory or retaliatory reasons\n\nHowever, most jurisdictions do maintain \"at-will\" employment principles, which mean employers can generally fire employees for almost any reason (except illegal reasons like discrimination), so there's still significant employer flexibility.\n\nSome specific exceptions where employers CAN fire employees include:\n- Poor job performance\n- Misconduct\n- Business restructuring\n- Economic necessity\n- Violation of company policies\n\nThe current legal framework tries to balance employer flexibility with employee protection, preventing extreme abuses while maintaining business operational needs.\n\nWould you be interested in hearing more about specific employment law principles?",
  "temperature": 1.0,
